content.description: Start in the dihedral left of the arete. Bolts 1 and 2 are just right of the arete. R rating unless stick clipping Bolt 2.

Slightly intimidating step off the boulder. Some cool jigsaw looking features. Then up to some tuffas out right, a long move up to a jug sidepull. A traverse left to a horizontal and up to a hard to see anchor on the left side of a block.
content.protection: 5 bolts and a Fixe sport anchor.
content.location: There is a boulder near the right end of the wall, this route starts off the left end of this boulder and climbs the interesting looking features straight up.

content.description:
Graded 5.10d in the guide book. This route is essentially a V2 boulder problem to get onto the wall followed by easy 5.10 climbing. 

  Reach from the ground up to the hollow looking and sounding flake that trends up and to the left. Pull on and hoist up into some pockets that really are not all that good. Once in the pockets stand up and continue up the face relatively easily to a thin section just below the anchors.
content.location: This route starts in the first steep low bulge you come to in the section. It is the furthest right route on the bulge and starts on a big flake that rises up and left. To the Left of Crankenstein.

content.description: Use Crankenstein's first bolt before moving left to bolts 2-4 of Bride of Crankenstein.
content.protection: 4 bolts with sport anchors at the top

content.description: Crux is the beginning towards the top. Stick clip the first bolt.

Fun start in the low bulge to nice pockets that get sharp the higher you go. Then a balency finish to the anchors. 

  This route though graded harder than its neighbor, War on Rugs, seems about the same in grade. It can be a bit dirty though because a lack of traffic.
content.location: This route starts in the first low bulge you come across in the area. Just to the left of the low flake that War on Rugs starts off of. Start from a high left side pull and a lower deep edge for the right.

content.description: From John Hogge's book: From the boulder, clip Bolt 1 of Wife, then go down to start on the ground. Bolts and anchors slant slightly left. Runout to Bolt 3 over a ledge hazard. Rick and several committee members support a retro.Â
content.protection: Bolts to I believe chains on top
content.location: Starts on Bolt 1 of Wife In The Fast Lane then slants slightly left

content.description:
Described as 12a in the guidebook, this route has been overgrown with vines and ivy until I cleaned it off today (12/6/2020). If you are under 6 feet tall you probably cant reach the juggy undercling full of ferns from the ground, but if you are you can, and if you can then you can skip the "12a" crux. That's stupid.Use a cheater stack to reach the undercling, or be tall and reach the undercling, climb through a low 5.10 crux to the flake, then enjoy fun 5.7 climbing to the anchors.

 Bolt 1 is on a protruding shield of rock, directly under the large flake. Stick clip this, climb directly up to it, then follow the flake to Scary 7-11's independent chains.
content.location: Three routes right of Crankenstein. Climbs the obvious flake system.

content.description: Start on Gang Bang. Move left after the first throw.
Small holds. yup

Climb through thin and bouldery cruxes using big moves, bad holds, or both, all separated by big jugs, with a final little crux guarding the anchors. The jug flake system to the right is off. The hardest moves are found directly in the boltline.
content.location: Just right of Industrial Disease, climbing to Industrial's anchors.

content.description: Bolt 1 is just above the curved edge of the roof.
The arete at the top is on-route.
Tough to get off the ground and onto the wall, then an interesting and reachy boulder problem up to, around and over the low roof. Above, easier face climbing on better holds up to the anchor.
content.location: Just right of Crankenstein, starting on the face/in the corner below a low roof.

climbs.name: Dude, where's my hammer?
climbs.fa: Luke Bowman, Tommy Blackwell, Evan Jackson

content.description: difficult start with no feet and hands reached high on slopers.  Couple of good moves to a very tiny undercling which leads to jugs below a bulge.  The bulge is tough to onsight but holds are plentiful if you look hard enough.
content.location: to the right of Die Hard

climbs.name: Die Hard
climbs.fa: Luke Bowman, Tommy Blackwell, Evan Jackson

content.description: The start is interesting climbing over a bulge (crux).  The top has fun stemming moves in the dihedral. This is a good warm-up for crankenstein wall.
content.location: Climbs the obvious dihedral left of a tree on the left half of crankenstein wall.

content.description: Make difficult moves up into some tuffa formations then over a roof. Some nice pocket holds lead up to a huge jug. some techy moves on sidepulls take you up to some mail slot type holds. A few more moves take you to huge flakes that are followed to the anchor.
content.location: Starts off a detached shelf of rock in the middle of the wall at a shallow corner arete. Just right of a long 45 degree section of wall.

content.description:
Start up the crack and quickly traverse back left to the second bolt on nice pockets. Work up the face to a difficult section getting to a ledge on the left of the line. Reach out right out clip the last bolt and make delicate moves out onto the face and up to jugs just below the anchor. 

  Based on how this is bolted the FA really wanted to keep you out of the crack, the first bolt is way left. However this would mean using a hollow undercling.
content.location: A the far right end of Crankenstien. Locate the two routes that start off of a boulder. The one on the left is Bolted Like Riemer's and the one on the right is Back off Crack. Clip a first bolt that is way left and start a bit to the right.

content.description:
Starts on the right of a large flat boulder. Route follows right leaning ramp up to a small roof. Anchors are just left of a large orange patch at the top. 

  Stick clip bolt 2 (and bolt 1 for the belayer) until you have this wired. 

  Large poison ivy plant dangles precariously close the the starting holds. Someone please pull that sucker!
content.location: Right of Wife in the Fast Lane

content.description: Stick clip the first bolt and start with your left hand in the obvious 3 finger pocket. Â The route initially moves right toward the start of Crankenstein but doesn't share holds.Â  The upper half of the route moves to the left.
content.protection: 4 bolts with sport anchors at the top

content.description: Back Off Crack is located on the far right side of Crankenstein wall.  Look for a pair of climbs that start of small boulders at the base of the wall and share and anchor.  Back Off Crack is the crack climb on the right with the lone bolt about two-thirds of the way up.  Climb the solid crack with great holds to the bolt.  Large stoppers and hexes are helpful, but you can also run it out to the bolt.  At the bolt, head left on thin face moves (crux) that lead to a shallow dihedral.  The holds and clipping stance at the anchors are pretty good.  One anchor is on the face and the second is above the rim.  Be prepared to rap off.
content.protection: Large stoppers/hexes protect the crack, one bolt protects the face moves at the top.  Two bolt anchor.

content.description: The start is just right of the bolt-line on a 3-finger horizontal right-hand slot just left of the chossy drip.
Start is 7' left of a 6" hackberry.
To the right of Grass Attack.

A true one move wonder.  Stand on the rock pile while assuring yourself that it wont crumble and then grab what feels like and has been said to be a chipped first hold. Then paste your feet and make a huge throw to a jug. After that its ample 5.9 to the top.
content.location: Starts on a man made cairn pile with a high first bolt

content.description: Right hand starts 3' right of the bolt-line.
typically hardmen and women frequent this area.
